ved the first electoral vote won by a woman, cast by [[Roger MacBride]].\n\n===1973===\nThe 1973 Convention was held in [[Strongsville, Ohio]] from June 8\u201310. Over 175 were in attendance.<ref>http://lpedia.org/w/images/d/d5/LPNews_1973-7_N15.pdf</ref>\n\n===1974===\nThe 1974 Convention adopted the [[Dallas Accord]] which sought to accommodate supporters of both [[anarcho-capitalism and minarchism]].<ref>Hihn, Mike. \"The Dallas Accord, Minarchists, and why our members sign a pledge\", Washington State Libertarian Party, August 2009.</ref><ref>Gottfried, Paul. ''The conservative movement: Social movements past and present '', Twayne Publishers, 1993, p. 46.</ref><ref>Antman, Less. [http://archive.lewrockwell.com/orig9/antman1.html The Dallas Accord is Dead], [[Lew Rockwell.com]], May 12, 2008.</ref>\n\n===1975===\nThe 1975 convention was held at the Statler-Hilton hotel in [[New York City]].&nbsp; [[Roger MacBride]] was nominated for president. After initially selecting [[None of the Above]], the Convention's delegates nominated [[David Bergland]] for vice president.\n\n===1976===\nThe 1976 convention was held in [[Washington, D.C.]], from September 23\u201326, 1976.\n\n===1977===\nThe 1977 Convention was held at the Palace Hotel in [[San Francisco, California]]. (More details soon)\n\n===1978===\nThe 1978 Convention was held at the Copley Plaza Hotel in Boston Massachusetts. (More details soon)\n\n===1979===\nThe 1979 Convention was held at the Bonaventure Hotel in Los Angeles<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bergland|first=David|date=January\u2013February 1979|title=From the Chair|url=|journal=Libertarian Party  News|volume=6|issue=45|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|via=}}</ref> and nominated [[Ed Clark]] for president and billionaire [[David H. Koch]] for vice president.\n\n===Alternative '80===\nThe 1980 Convention was held at the Century City Hotel in [[Los Angeles, California]] and via satellite.&nbsp; Unlike other Libertarian Party conventions, its primary purpose was promotional.\n\n===1981===\nThe 1981 Convention was held in [[Denver, Colorado]].\n\n===1983===\n{{Main|1983 Libertarian National Convention}}\n[[David Bergland]] was selected as the 1984 presidential nominee at the [[1983 Libertarian National Convention|1983]] National Convention.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theadvocates.org/celebrities/david-bergland.html |title=David Bergland - Libertarian |publisher=[[Advocates for Self-Government]] via [[Internet Archive]] |accessdate=May 28, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080407232233/http://www.theadvocates.org/celebrities/david-bergland.html |archivedate=April 7, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===1985===\nThe 1985 Convention was held in [[Phoenix, Arizona]].\n\n===1987===\n{{Main|1987 Libertarian National Convention}}\nThe [[1987 Libertarian National Convention]] was held the first weekend in September in [[Seattle, Washington]]. At the Convention, the party was split between conservative and liberal factions.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://civilliberty.about.com/b/2008/05/26/the-libertarian-party-takes-a-hard-right-turn.htm | title=The Libertarian Party Takes a Hard Right Turn | author=Head, Tom | date=May 26, 2008 |accessdate=May 17, 2012}}</ref>&nbsp; [[Ron Paul]], representing the former, was nominated as the Libertarian Party's 1988 presidential candidate on the first ballot with 196 of the 368 votes cast.&nbsp; His closest opponent, [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] activist [[Russell Means]], received 120 votes.<ref name=nyt88>{{citation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/06/us/libertarians-pick-ex-congressman-in-88-bid.html |title=Libertarians Pick Ex-Congressman in '88 Bid |first=Wallace |last=Turner |newspaper=New York Times |publication-place=New York, New York |date=September 6, 1987 |page=35 }}</ref>&nbsp; [[Andre Marrou]] was selected as Paul's running mate as the candidate for Vice President without opposition.<ref name=nyt88/>\n\n===1989===\nThe 1989 Convention was held in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].\n\n===1991===\n{{Main|1991 Libertarian National Convention}}\nThe [[1991 Libertarian National Convention]] was held in [[Chicago]] the last weekend in August, and nominated [[Andre Marrou]] as the party's 1992 candidate for president.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1082708.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231073348/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1082708.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=December 31, 2013 | title=Libertarian Party Nominates Real Estate Broker for Run at a Million Votes | work=[[The Washington Post]] via [[HighBeam Research]] {{Subscription required}}| date=September 1, 1991 | accessdate=May 6, 2012 | author=Walsh, Edward}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4133531.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808120314/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4133531.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=August 8, 2014 | title=To Libertarian, Less Is More | work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] via HighBeam Research {{subscription required}} | date=October 7, 1992 | accessdate=May 6, 2012 | author=O'Donnell, Maureen}}</ref>\n\n===1993===\nThe 1993 Convention was held in [[Salt Lake City, Utah]].\n\n===1996===\n{{Main|1996 Libertarian National Convention}}\nThe [[1996 Libertarian National Convention]] was held the first weekend of July in [[Washington D.C.]] and nominated [[Harry Browne]] as its presidential candidate.<ref>{{cite interview | url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/election/july96/browne_7-10.html | title=Strict Interpretation | subject=Browne, Harry | interviewer=Hunter-Gault, Charlayne | publisher=[[PBS]] | date=July 10, 1996 | accessdate=May 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===1998===\nThe 1998 Convention was held in [[Washington D.C.]]\n\n===2000===\n{{Main|2000 Libertarian National Convention}}\nThe 2000 Convention was held in [[Anaheim, California]], from June 30 to July 4.&nbsp; [[Harry Browne]] was again chosen as the party's presidential candidate, becoming the first Libertarian Party candidate to run twice for President of the United States.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oakkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TG8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3355,2388945&dq=2000+libertarian+national+convention+-wikipedia&hl=en | title=Libertarians nominate Browne for presidency | author=Werner, Erica | work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] | publisher=Associated Press | date=July 3, 2000 | accessdate=May 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2002===\nThe 2002 Convention was held in [[Indianapolis, Indiana]], from July 3 to 7.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dehnbase.org/lpus/library/lnc-candidates-2002.html | title=Candidates for Libertarian National Committee | accessdate=May 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2004===\n{{Main|2004 Libertarian National Convention}}\nThe 2004 Convention was held at the Marriott Marquis Hotel in [[Atlanta, Georgia]] Memorial Day weekend, May 27 to May 31. [[Michael Badnarik]] was chosen as the party's presidential candidate, beating out [[Gary Nolan (radio host)|Gary Nolan]] and [[Aaron Russo]] on the third ballot; [[Richard Campagna]] was chosen as the party's vice-presidential candidate over [[Tamara Millay]], and [[Michael Dixon (politician)|Michael Dixon]] was elected chair of the LNC.\n\n===2006===\nThe 2006 Convention was held at the Hilton Portland & Executive Tower in [[Portland, Oregon]], July 1\u20132.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lp.org/archives/lpnatconv2006.pdf | title=2006 National Convention Portland, Oregon Draft Minutes | date=February 17, 2007 | accessdate=May 3, 2012 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511111828/http://www.lp.org/archives/lpnatconv2006.pdf | archivedate=May 11, 2012 }}</ref>&nbsp; Delegates chose (in a \"retain or delete\" vote process) to eliminate about three quarters of the specific planks in the party's platform<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060712194813/http://www.lp.org/media/article_368.shtml ''LP News''], 07/12/06</ref>\n\nSpeakers included:\n* [[Michael Badnarik]], candidate for U.S. House of Representatives (TX-10) and the 2004 Libertarian Presidential candidate\n* Judge [[John A. Buttrick]], Maricopa County (Arizona) Superior Court Judge, 1994 Arizona gubernatorial candidate, 1998 Arizona House of Representatives candidate\n* Megan Dickson, an eighth-grade honors student who spoke about [[libertarianism]]\n* Patrick Dixon, city councilman, Lago Vista, Texas\n* Bill Lynn, Alderman, Davenport, Iowa\n* [[Tonie Nathan]], former Libertarian Vice-Presidential candidate, and the first woman to receive an electoral vote in U.S. history\n* BetteRose Ryan,  at-large LNC member\n* Rev. Anthony Williams, candidate for U.S. House of Representatives (IL-2)\n* Former Congressman [[Bob Barr]], who has served as the chairman of Patriots to Restore Checks and Balances\n* [[Andrew Neil]], founding chairman of [[British Sky Broadcasting|Sky TV]], former publisher of ''[[The Scotsman]]'', former editor of ''[[The Economist]]'' and former editor-in-chief of the [[The Sunday Times (UK)|Sunday Times]]\n* Christopher J. Farrell, member of the [[Judicial Watch]]'s Board of Directors\n* Greg Nojeim, associate director and chief legislative counsel for the ACLU\n* [[Krist Novoselic]], founding member of the Seattle-based grunge rock band [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], founder JAMPAC (Joint Artists and Music Promotions Political Action Committee), author of ''Of Grunge and Government: Let's Fix This Broken Democracy''\n\n===2008===\n{{Location map+|USA|width=250|float=right|caption=Sites of the 2008 national conventions.|places=\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=blue-gold pog.svg|marksize=14|lat_deg=39.739167|lon_deg=-104.984722|position=left|background=#FFFFFF|label='''Denver'''}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=red pog.svg|lat_deg=44.9441|lon_deg=-93.0852|position=top|background=#FFFFFF|label=Saint Paul}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=purple pog.svg|lat_deg=39.1|lon_deg=-94.58|position=bottom|background=#FFFFFF|label=Kansas City}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=green pog.svg|lat_deg=41.836944|lon_deg=-87.684444|position=right|background=#FFFFFF|label=Chicago}}\n}}{{Main|2008 Libertarian National Convention}}\nThe 2008 convention was held at the Sheraton Denver Downtown Hotel (formerly the Adam's Mark Hotel) in [[Denver, Colorado]] (the same city as the very first convention in 1972), May 23\u201326.\n{{clear}}\n\n===2010===\n{{Main|2010 Libertarian National Convention}}\nThe 2010 Convention was held in [[St. Louis, Missouri]] from Friday May 28 to Monday May 31.\n\n===2012===\n{{Location map many | USA |left| width=250 |caption=Sites of the 2012 national conventions.\n| mark1=blue pog.svg | mark1size=8 | lat1_deg=35.2269 | lon1_deg=-80.843333 | label1=Charlotte | position1=bottom\n| mark2=red pog.svg | mark2size=8 | lat2_deg=27.9709 | lon2_deg=-82.46464 | label2=Tampa | position2=left\n| mark3=purple pog.svg | mark3size=8 | lat3_deg=36.165 |lon3_deg=-86.784 | label3=Nashville | position3=left\n| mark4=yellow pog.svg | mark4size=14 | lat4_deg=36.176 | lon4_deg=-115.137 | label4='''Las Vegas''' | position4=top\n| mark5=green pog.svg | mark5size=8 | lat5_deg=39.283333 | lon5_deg=-76.616667 | label5=Baltimore | position5=left\n}}{{Main|2012 Libertarian National Convention}}\nThe 2012 convention was held in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] May 4\u20136, 2012.<ref>Myers, Laura (November 30, 2010) [http://www.lvrj.com/news/las-vegas-will-host-libertarian-convention-111027874.html \"Las Vegas will host Libertarian convention\"], ''[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]''. Retrieved November 30, 2010.</ref><ref>Malcolm, Andrew (November 30, 2010) [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/washington/2010/11/las-vegas-libertarian-party.html \"Las Vegas gets its first national political convention\"], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Retrieved November 30, 2010.</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===2014===\n{{Main|2014 Libertarian National Convention}}\nThe 2014 Convention was held in [[Columbus, Ohio]] during the last weekend in June.<ref name=\"Official Website 2014\">{{Cite web |url=http://lpcon2014.org/ |title=Official Website 2014 |access-date=2014-03-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221080120/https://lpcon2014.org/ |archive-date=2014-12-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===2016===\n{{Location map many | USA |left| width=250 |caption=Sites of the 2016 national conventions.\n| alt=Map of United States showing Orlando, Florida\n| mark1=yellow pog.svg | mark1size=14 | lat1_deg=28.245 | lon1_deg=-81.175 | label1='''Orlando''' | position1=top\n| mark2=red pog.svg | mark2size=8 | lat2_deg=41.285 |lon2_deg=-81.401 | label2=Cleveland | position2=top\n| mark3=blue pog.svg | mark3size=8 | lat3_deg=39.57 | lon3_deg=-75.10 | label3=Philadelphia | position3=bottom\n| mark4=green pog.svg | mark4size=8 | lat4_deg=29.454 | lon4_deg=-95.225 | label4=Houston | position4=left\n}}{{Main|2016 Libertarian National Convention}}\nThe 2016 convention was held in [[Orlando, Florida]] during the last weekend in May.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://reason.com/reasontv/2016/06/03/what-would-success-and-failure-look-like | title=What Would Success (or Failure) Look Like for the Libertarian Party This Year? | work=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]].com | date=June 3, 2016 | accessdate=June 27, 2016 |author1=Weissmueller, Zach |author2=Swain, Joshua }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===2018===\n{{Main|2018 Libertarian National Convention}}\nThe 2018 convention was held from June 30 to July 3 in New Orleans, Louisiana. Nicholas Sarwark was reelected as chair, Alex Merced elected as Vice-Chair, Caryn Ann Harlos elected as Secretary, Tim Hagan reelected as Treasurer, new At-Large members were selected, and a new four-year term Judicial Committee was elected.\n\n===2020===\n{{Main|2020 Libertarian National Convention}} \nThe 2020 convention is scheduled to be held in [[Austin, Texas]] over [[Memorial Day]] weekend.\n\n==List of Libertarian conventions==\nThe following is a list of [[United States]] [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] [[U.S. presidential nominating convention|Presidential nominating conventions]].\n\n{| border=2 align=center\n|-\n!width=70px align=center|Year\n!width=120px align=center|Location\n!width=205px align=center|Presidential Nominee\n!width=220px align=center|Vice Presidential Nominee\n|-\n|align=center height=40px|[[1972 Libertarian National Convention|1972]]\n|align=center|[[Denver, Colorado|Denver]]\n|align=center|[[John Hospers]] of [[California]]\n|align=center|[[Theodora Nathan]] of [[Oregon]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[1973 Libertarian National Convention|1973]]\n|align=center|[[Strongsville, Ohio|Strongsville]]\n|colspan=2 rowspan=2 align=center|N/A\n|-\n|align=center|[[1974 Libertarian National Convention|1974]]\n|align=center|[[Irving, Texas|Irving]]\n|-\n|align=center height=40px|[[1975 Libertarian National Convention|1975]]\n|align=center|[[New York, New York|New York]]\n|align=center|[[Roger MacBride]] of [[Virginia]]\n|align=center|[[David Bergland]] of [[California]]\n|-\n|align=center height=40px|[[1977 Libertarian National Convention|1977]]\n|align=center|[[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|N/A\n|-\n|align=center|[[1979 Libertarian National Convention|1979]]\n|align=center rowspan=2|[[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]]\n|align=center rowspan=2|[[Ed Clark]] of [[California]]\n|align=center rowspan=2|[[David H. Koch|David Koch]] of [[Kansas]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[Alternative '80|1980]]\n|-\n|align=center height=40px|[[1981 Libertarian National Convention|1981]]\n|align=center|[[Denver, Colorado|Denver]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|N/A\n|-\n|align=center height=40px|[[1983 Libertarian National Convention|1983]]\n|align=center|[[New York, New York|New York]]\n|align=center|[[David Bergland]] of [[California]]\n|align=center|[[James A. Lewis|James Lewis]] of [[Connecticut]]\n|-\n|align=center height=40px|[[1985 Libertarian National Convention|1985]]\n|align=center|[[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]\n|colspan=2 align=center|N/A\n|-\n|align=center height=40px|[[1987 Libertari